properties.name: Treaty with South Carolina
properties.description:
Both Royce (1887) and Mooney (1975 [1900]) attribute the first transfer of land between Cherokees and English colonists to a 1721 agreement between the Cherokees and Governor Nicholson of South Carolina. Mooney writes:

“In 1721, in order still more to systematize Indian affairs, Governor Nicholson of South Carolina invited the chiefs of the Cherokee to a conference, at which thirty-seven towns were represented. A treaty was made by which trading methods were regulated, a boundary line between their territory and the English settlements was agreed upon, and an agent was appointed to superintend their affairs… The negotiations were accompanied by a cession of land, the first in the history of the tribe. In little more than a century thereafter they had signed away their whole original territory” (Mooney 1975 [1900]).

Similarly, Royce’s “Map of the Former Territorial Limits of the Cherokee ‘Nation’ of Indians…” pictures a 1721 cession as the first of thirty-six territorial losses culminating in the final land cession of 1835 (Royce 1887).

A more recent scholar of Southeastern geography, Louis De Vorsey, concedes that there were “probably” land cessions made to South Carolina by the Cherokee Indians in the first half of the 18th Century, but warns us that Royce’s map “contains several errors and should not be accepted as authoritative” (De Vorsey 1966).

In the absence of conflicting evidence, however, I have chosen to reconstruct the boundaries of the 1721 “cession” to conform to Royce’s map. However, we should treat both the geographical and legal integrity of this territory as highly speculative, for two reasons.

First, it is doubtful that the concept of a land cession was mutually understood by the South Carolinians and Cherokees at this early date. The earliest historical record of the 1721 agreement appears to come from Hewat (1779). The sole reference to a land transaction appears in the following sentence: “At this congress the Governor having made them several presents, and smoked the pipe of peace with them, marked the boundaries of the lands between them and the English settlers” (Hewatt 1779).

Although the English may have regarded these marked boundaries as denoting a cession of territory in a Western sense, the Cherokees likely did not. As late as the 1740s and 1750s, conflicts between Cherokees and colonists were often the result of differing notions of land ownership. The Cherokees did not realize that, in the English understanding, boundary lines precluded their right to travel and hunt in the ceded territory. Conflicts arising from this misunderstanding culminated in the Long Canes Massacre and the Cherokee War of 1760–1761, after which the language of treaties became more explicit about the nature of land use (Cook 2017).

A second reason for skepticism of the land cession as shown on the map is the absence of a contemporary geographical description of the 1721 boundary line. To my knowledge, Royce’s map is the only cartographic representation of the “Treaty of 1721,” and it was created over 160 years after the fact. On his map, Royce describes the bounds of the cession as “between the Santee and Saluda and Edisto Rivers,” but gives no source. Perhaps he determined these bounds by comparing historic maps from before and after 1721, but I cannot be sure. I have provided more detail in the descriptions accompanying the individual segments of this boundary line.

properties.name: Pre-Cession Territorial Claim
properties.description:
The non-darkened area of the map shows the approximate extent of Cherokee territory around the year 1715.

In drawing this area, I have chosen to largely follow the bounds that Charles C. Royce (1887) mapped and described as the Cherokees’ territorial limits prior to their first cession of land to European settlers. Royce’s map is perhaps the most ubiquitous representation of historical Cherokee geography in existence, despite several flaws. (Scholar of Southeastern geography Louis De Vorsey (1966) warned that Royce’s map contains errors and “should not be accepted as authoritative.”)

Nevertheless, the outer bounds of Cherokee territory depicted on the map have been accepted by modern researchers. Bolstad and Gragson (2007, 438) argue that Royce’s boundaries “correspond to the maximum geographic space used by the eighteenth‐century Cherokee to satisfy various social, political, and economic needs based on eyewitness accounts, oral history, and modeling.”

The vast majority of the approximately 125,000 square mile territory shown here contained no permanent towns or villages and was used exclusively as hunting grounds. By the beginning of the eighteenth century, most Cherokee economic and social life took place within a core heartland of about 60 towns in the mountains and foothills of the southern Blue Ridge in the present states of North Carolina, South Carolina, Tennessee, and Georgia (Gragson and Bolstad 2007; Thornton, 1990, 11, 24). Beyond this core area, the Cherokee hunting grounds ranged for hundreds of miles in each direction, in some places overlapping with those of their indigenous neighbors. To the extent that Amerindians may have delineated precise limits for their hunting grounds, those boundaries were porous and impermanent.

Nevertheless, I have made my best attempt to transcribe the outer bounds of Royce’s map onto precise geographic coordinates based on his descriptions, on additional documentary sources, and where applicable, in conformity to natural features like rivers and drainage divides. Although supposedly depicting the Cherokee territorial claim in the early eighteenth century, some portions of the outer boundary (particularly the southern portion separating the Cherokees from the Creeks and Chickasaws) follow lines not described or surveyed until well into the nineteenth century. While unsatisfying, these nineteenth-century treaty boundaries are as accurate a reflection of eighteenth-century boundaries as the historical record affords.

In choosing a date to depict pre-cession Cherokee territory, I have chosen a fixed date of 1715 for two reasons. First, a fixed date is necessary because Cherokee territory was not static from time immemorial. Indeed, the extent of the Cherokee domain at this time may well have been at its historical peak, having expanded to fill spaces vacated by their indigenous neighbors to the east, south, and west who bore the brunt of Spanish entradas and the Carolina trade in Indian slaves (Thornton 1990, 12).

Second, 1715 is approximately the date by which the Shawnees had abandoned their position in present-day middle Tennessee and removed beyond the Ohio River after several years of warfare with the Cherokees and Chickasaws (Mooney 1975 [1900], 38, 371). Much of the western portion of the Cherokees’ territorial claim as shown on Royce’s map was thus a brand new addition in 1715.
